President Donald Trump has announced new security measures aimed at establishing minimum requirements for international cooperation to support visa and immigration vetting for individuals seeking entry to the United States. The Department of Homeland Security, in collaboration with other agencies, developed the new baseline requirements based on international norms and best practices. Countries that fail to meet these requirements may face travel restrictions for their nationals. Most countries have met the new baseline, while some are not yet in compliance. The restrictions will be lifted as countries work with the United States to ensure the safety of Americans. The article provides additional information in the form of a Fact Sheet and FAQ.